objective:
Fix 3 reliability bugs: cross-project env variable leakage via mutable global _extra_env_keys in config.py, semaphore recreation silently breaking dynamic worker count adjustment in continuous_controller.py _dispatch_loop, and add end-to-end integration test covering the full dispatch-merge-complete critical path

Priority backlog items to address:
1. [security] Fix cross-project env variable leakage via global _extra_env_keys (backlog_item_id=1655f559bf57, priority=7.5): In config.py, `_extra_env_keys` is a module-level mutable global (line 998). `load_config()` overwrites it with `global _extra_env_keys`. When the multi-project registry loads configs for multiple projects concurrently, whichever `load_config` call finishes last wins. `claude_subprocess_env()` at line 1001 reads this global, so a worker spawned for project A may receive the extra environment keys (potentially containing secrets) configured for project B. Replace the global with a per-config instance attribute, passing it through the config object to `claude_subprocess_env()`.
2. [quality] Fix single-command verification marking unrun checks as passed (backlog_item_id=cb9cf8e8077e, priority=7.5): In state.py `_build_result_from_single_command` (line 113), when the combined `pytest && ruff` command exits 0, ALL 4 verification nodes (pytest, ruff, mypy, bandit) are unconditionally marked `passed=True` -- even though mypy and bandit were never actually executed. The metrics dict will show `type_errors=0` and `security_findings=0` not because there are none, but because the output contains no mypy/bandit output. This creates a false-positive in verification scoring. Only mark nodes as passed if their parser actually found relevant output, or explicitly mark unrun nodes with a distinct status.
3. [security] Fix cross-project env variable leakage via global _extra_env_keys (backlog_item_id=97a9f0eed194, priority=7.5): In config.py, `_extra_env_keys` is a module-level mutable global (line 998). `load_config()` overwrites it with `global _extra_env_keys`. When the multi-project registry loads configs for multiple projects concurrently, whichever `load_config` call finishes last wins. `claude_subprocess_env()` at line 1001 reads this global, so a worker spawned for project A may receive the extra environment keys (potentially containing secrets) configured for project B. Replace the global with a per-config instance attribute, passing it through the config object to `claude_subprocess_env()`.
4. [feature] Add cross-mission learning to the strategist via episodic memory (backlog_item_id=f32465380d30, priority=7.2): The strategist.py proposes objectives and scores ambition, but starts fresh each mission with no memory of what worked previously. Implement a feedback loop: after each mission completes, persist a mission summary (objective, units completed, conflict rate, duration, final verification result) to the database. On next mission start, load the last N mission summaries as context for the strategist prompt. This lets the strategist avoid re-proposing objectives that failed, learn which ambition levels succeed for this codebase, and build on prior progress. The episodic_semantic memory infrastructure and event_sourcing tables already exist in the DB -- wire them into the strategist's prompt context.
5. [quality] Add end-to-end integration test for the dispatch-merge-complete cycle (backlog_item_id=21a7be9df21e, priority=7.2): The critical path (controller dispatches unit -> worker executes -> MC_RESULT parsed -> green branch merge -> handoff ingested -> planner re-plans) is only tested at the unit level in separate test files. Create an integration test in tests/test_integration_cycle.py that: (1) sets up a real git repo in tmp_path, (2) initializes a controller with a mock worker backend that produces realistic MC_RESULT output, (3) runs 2-3 work units through the full cycle including merge to mc/green, (4) verifies the final git state, db state, and mission state updates. Use the existing real-git test pattern from test_green_branch.py (TestGreenBranchRealGit) as a foundation.
